It wasn't just like, we're going to get together and bang out a problem really quickly. You really

00:21:49.199 --> 00:21:53.520
centered the learning and expanding everybody's horizons around the topic. So could you talk a

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:56.800
little bit about how you did that? Because I think other people would love to do this too.

00:21:57.520 --> 00:22:03.199
Yes. So this happened in November. So we typically have two hackathons a year,

00:22:03.199 --> 00:22:08.959
and I kind of hijacked this one for this purpose. So what I really wanted was there

00:22:08.959 --> 00:22:14.800
was a growing interest in the company with LLMs and different people were excited to try things.

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:20.000
We had set up an internal community called the AI Builders Community. It's a Slack channel where

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:25.280
people who are building with this could come and ask questions and we would support. But the one

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:29.920
thing I realized was, I think, as Abigail mentioned, that there was no context to how

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:34.880
these models were working. And so people would try things and be sometimes frustrated with not

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:41.040
getting quite the output they want. And the other thing that I was noticing was people,

00:22:41.599 --> 00:22:44.800
I think it's happened to us many times, is we get so enamored by the technology,

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:49.040
we forget what we're solving. So it's like at the end of the day, we're solving user problems,

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:53.359
we're solving some problem for ourselves or we're solving some problem for our customers.

00:22:53.359 --> 00:22:57.760
And so you want to center it around that when you're solving, even with an LLM,

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:01.359
because it doesn't matter if it's an LLM or XGBoost or the other, it doesn't matter,

00:23:01.359 --> 00:23:08.719
as long as it's solving a real problem. So what we did was we kind of did a few things. So

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:16.479
one, we said that part of the hackathon would be learning. And one learning was obviously the

00:23:16.479 --> 00:23:21.119
technical side of things. We went through how LLMs work, we went through how to evaluate them,

00:23:21.119 --> 00:23:27.280
how to think about evaluations. I also had one section on security and what these APIs are,

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:32.160
what data should you throw in, what should you not, and how should that work. And then another

00:23:32.160 --> 00:23:38.239
piece of it was that I also invited my head of design and her group to talk about customer

00:23:38.239 --> 00:23:45.280
centricity. What does it mean? How to do a mind mapping, how to think about a customer problem

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:49.599
and how to center yourselves on the customer problem. So we had these two sides of like,

00:23:49.599 --> 00:23:54.319
let's think about the customer, let's understand this technology and let's put it together for a

00:23:54.319 --> 00:24:01.920
couple of days of hack to come up with something interesting and useful. And one other piece that

00:24:01.920 --> 00:24:09.760
we did was we gave each team a mentor, an executive mentor, like from our VP, CTO, VP level and up,

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:13.760
so that they could kind of see what these teams are building and they could guide the team from

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:18.640
the perspective of like, you know, will this solution be useful? Like what are some things

00:24:18.640 --> 00:24:22.319
to think about? Because we think about the technicalities like hallucination, but

00:24:22.319 --> 00:24:26.719
there's also an individual or a human on the other side who's going to use it. So kind of

00:24:26.719 --> 00:24:32.000
centering them around what to think about, what's the business problem, like what benefits should we

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:39.040
see? So we also gave mentors. Also at the end of the hackathon, I organized these office hours with

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:44.560
my principal and staff engineers so that people could come and just vet their solutions. They

00:24:44.560 --> 00:24:48.239
could just tell them what they built. So one, the engineers have a sense of like, what's going to

00:24:48.239 --> 00:24:51.280
come downstream? Like what's going to come two months from now? Because many of these solutions

00:24:51.280 --> 00:24:56.079
are quite productizable, so what's going to come downstream? But they could also give them

00:24:57.280 --> 00:25:01.199
some insights into, hey, what are some caveats that could happen in production? Like what are

00:25:01.199 --> 00:25:05.760
some things to think about? Like latency is a big issue with LLMs, like we all know that.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:10.719
So if you're expecting a system that needs a fast response, then latency is something you

00:25:10.719 --> 00:25:15.119
have to consider. So we had an office hours with a bunch of our senior engineers across these

00:25:15.119 --> 00:25:23.839
different domains, data, product, infrastructure, and so they could give their advice. And so what

00:25:23.839 --> 00:25:28.079
they had to present was their solution, but they also had to present their learnings and the

00:25:28.079 --> 00:25:33.040
feedback they got from this engineering group of like, what does it take to take this feature into

00:25:33.040 --> 00:25:37.839
production? So yeah, that was kind of, I think I covered most of the pieces, so.

00:25:37.839 --> 00:25:43.520
Yeah, that's amazing. How many days did this last? I'm wondering.

