can be able to replace some of the, maybe most of the data science work. So what do you view about

00:27:27.680 --> 00:27:33.760
that? Sorry, too long. No, no, no, no. It's a good question. The short answer, I think we learn along

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:38.640
the way. That's the short answer. But I can tell you what we think about and how we, you know, we

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:44.800
think about. So for LLMs, I think there's two parts. So I'll talk about one part very briefly,

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:50.719
because I think Ron has questions more around the cost. One is just, you know, evaluations and, you

00:27:50.719 --> 00:27:54.719
know, actually putting your evaluation set together, actually getting your metrics in place,

00:27:54.719 --> 00:27:59.280
doing qualitative and quantitative validations, kind of knowing where the boundaries of your,

00:28:01.119 --> 00:28:05.439
you know, of your, you know, failures are like, where are you going to fail?

00:28:06.479 --> 00:28:10.640
You know, having to actually collect manual label data. People think label data has gone away. It

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:14.160
hasn't. Like you still have to evaluate the model, even though you don't need the millions of data

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:20.479
points to train it, you still need some set to like validate it. So that has to happen. So without

00:28:20.479 --> 00:28:25.119
that, that's a big part of the support we're giving and the coaching we're giving is just that

00:28:25.119 --> 00:28:29.760
just because it works for a couple of examples, doesn't mean this works. And you still have to

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:34.000
validate it with the same rigor you would any other machine learning model. I think from a cost

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:40.719
perspective, I think I was definitely nervous when everybody got excited about LLMs. My first

00:28:40.719 --> 00:28:46.640
instinct was also that, oh my God, cost is going to go through the roof. And what I realized was

00:28:46.640 --> 00:28:56.000
I was the person who needed to solve for it. And so what we do is, yes, these OpenAI endpoints,

00:28:56.560 --> 00:29:01.839
you know, as you scale or any other like Anthropic or any other endpoints that you use

00:29:01.839 --> 00:29:09.119
can get expensive over time, definitely. But I think what they help you do is kind of evaluate

00:29:09.119 --> 00:29:15.199
your use case really fast, right? Because one of these things we don't know about these LLM type

00:29:16.160 --> 00:29:20.959
features is you don't know, especially if you're putting out a customer feature, you don't know

00:29:20.959 --> 00:29:24.800
whether customers will like it in the first place. Like you don't know how they will interact with it.

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:29.680
You don't know whether it's going to be good enough. And so the key thing with AI, and I think

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:33.760
it's always been true with ML, but I think with LLMs it's also true is the iterations are important.

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:38.959
Like how fast can you ship a version and how fast can you get feedback from it? And these LLM

00:29:39.199 --> 00:29:46.160
endpoints from these other companies really enable that. They make it really easy to do that.

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:54.160
Like you can put an API in and get some feedback really quickly. But I think one of the ways that

00:29:54.160 --> 00:30:01.199
I have built out or we continue to build out these kinds of endpoints is the product, well,

00:30:01.199 --> 00:30:06.800
the product feature, we're the ML platform team. We build, you know, just very common patterns. We

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:11.520
build an API. So we kind of encapsulate. So the product doesn't hit OpenAI directly. We have an

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:17.280
encapsulation layer. They hit it through us. We hit OpenAI. And I've already started, we've started

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:21.359
doing experiments on small language models. Like we start training on our own data and then getting

00:30:21.359 --> 00:30:27.680
more specific models in-house and seeing if, you know, like basically getting, get ready for the

00:30:28.560 --> 00:30:35.119
point when we'll have to like potentially remove these OpenAI type endpoints and then maybe replace

00:30:35.119 --> 00:30:40.880
them with smaller, maybe use case-specific, context-specific models. That's experiment

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:46.160
that's ongoing right now. Will we be super successful? Can these models fully replace them?

00:30:47.199 --> 00:30:51.199
It's definitely a question to be answered. I don't have an exact answer right now,

00:30:51.199 --> 00:30:54.719
but my thought process is like making sure that the product is not affected. So making sure that

00:30:54.719 --> 00:31:00.400
everything's encapsulated and set up in my side. And yes, it's going to be expensive in the short

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:04.800
term, hopefully until like we figured out what features to build. But the longer term strategy

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:10.239
is always going to be building models with our own data. One, it can have a lot of context of

00:31:10.239 --> 00:31:18.400
our company, but also it'll probably be more effective. And of course, a bigger part of

00:31:18.400 --> 00:31:24.079
our discussions always doesn't even need an LLM. Can we replace it with a much simpler model? And

00:31:24.079 --> 00:31:26.880
for many use cases, it could very well be the case. Like we can probably,

00:31:27.520 --> 00:31:31.359
an LLM is a short answer, but it doesn't have to be the long-term strategy. So we may not even go

00:31:31.359 --> 00:31:39.599
with an LLM. Six months down, we may replace it with a bunch of simpler models. But that's

00:31:39.599 --> 00:31:42.959
definitely a learning that I'm having as well. So if I'm going to hang out one year from now,

00:31:42.959 --> 00:31:46.239
I may have more firmer answers on how that exploration is going.

