and it has an asterisk, so I will ask it, but there's a little bit of discussion about it in

00:36:32.719 --> 00:36:36.879
the chat. I think it's a great question. He says, when building a predictive model,

00:36:36.879 --> 00:36:42.719
how do you find the right balance between ensuring the model is explainable versus

00:36:42.719 --> 00:36:48.959
how accurate it is? Do you often see situations where an AI or machine learning model is less

00:36:48.959 --> 00:36:53.439
ideal than a simpler model? I'm assuming because a simpler model is probably more explainable.

00:36:53.439 --> 00:37:01.760
Yeah, it's a good, it's always a good question. I think the general

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:08.399
rule of thumb, at least we've, we've tried and it's not perfect, is,

00:37:10.879 --> 00:37:16.000
and also explainability is interesting because like it's, it's like, you know, explainability

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:20.000
itself, almost a lot of explainable models, unless you're using a linear regression model itself is

00:37:20.959 --> 00:37:26.399
another model that is, is kind of running a certain scenario and putting together what

00:37:26.399 --> 00:37:37.280
it's gathering. So for the models that were more, I think, risk-based, I mean,

00:37:37.280 --> 00:37:43.120
things that were determining if someone would, we have a product called Cashouts. So we have

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:47.120
models that, you know, that internally we have risk assessment of like, you know, when people

00:37:47.120 --> 00:37:52.479
are drawing cashouts, you obviously want to be, there's a responsibility angle to it, right? Like

00:37:52.479 --> 00:37:57.040
even if the business may not think about it as a data scientist, we have a code of ethics. We

00:37:57.040 --> 00:38:00.800
write up for data science, we have a conference page that says, we have a code of ethics that

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:05.280
says do no harm, like make sure that you're not biased and you know, all of that. So we,

00:38:05.280 --> 00:38:11.840
we try to make those models as much as possible explainable. And, and the one thing we do is

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:19.280
we don't reject anybody, if you know what I'm saying, like everybody gets a minimum of

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:23.280
something, right? Like there's no, like the model will not make a decision

00:38:23.919 --> 00:38:29.120
in the negative. And we make sure that when there's a negative decision, that it, a minimum

00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:33.199
is given and there is a review. There's something else happens beyond that. It's, it's never a model

00:38:33.199 --> 00:38:38.800
making a decision. So we, we try to balance out like trying models that are a bit more explainable

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:46.800
and making sure that there are business rules around not just blindly saying no to somebody

00:38:47.439 --> 00:38:56.239
